import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const title = `Before the Nolan Film — Read the Odyssey Before July 17, 2026`;
const description = `Christopher Nolan's The Odyssey starring Matt Damon, Tom Holland, and Zendaya releases July 17, 2026.`;
const canonical = `https://readingtheodyssey.com/before-the-nolan-film`;
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} activePage="before-the-nolan-film">
  <article class="section active">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-label">The Film</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Before the Nolan Film</h2>
      <p class="section-subtitle">Everything you need to read the Odyssey before July 17, 2026</p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-body">

      <a class="trailer-link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mzw2ttJD2qQ" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <div class="trailer-thumbnail">
          <img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/Mzw2ttJD2qQ/maxresdefault.jpg" alt="Christopher Nolan's The Odyssey — Official Trailer" />
          <div class="trailer-play">▶</div>
        </div>
      </a>

      <p>Christopher Nolan's The Odyssey releases July 17, 2026 — starring Matt Damon as Odysseus, Tom Holland as Telemachus, and Zendaya. If you want to read Homer's epic before you see the film, this page tells you exactly how to do it.</p>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">How Long Does It Actually Take?</div>
        <div class="book-author">Less time than you think</div>
        <div class="book-note">The Odyssey is 24 books and roughly 12,000 lines — but it reads faster than the Iliad. Most readers finish in 10-15 hours of reading time. At an hour a day you can read the entire poem in two weeks. At two hours on weekends you can finish it in a month. You have time.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">Which Translation to Read</div>
        <div class="book-author">For first-time readers preparing for the film</div>
        <div class="book-note">Start with Emily Wilson (2017) — the most modern, most readable translation, and the one most likely to feel cinematic. Her version is direct, clear, and emotionally alive in a way that suits readers coming to Homer for the first time. Robert Fagles is the strong second choice if you want something slightly more epic in register. Either will prepare you well for what Nolan is working with.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">The Cast Mapped to Homer</div>
        <div class="book-author">Who Nolan's actors are playing</div>
        <div class="book-note">Matt Damon plays Odysseus — the man of many turns, the cunning survivor, the king trying to get home. Tom Holland plays Telemachus — Odysseus's son, who spends the first four books searching for news of his missing father. Zendaya's role has not been confirmed, but the most prominent women in the poem are Penelope (the faithful wife), Circe (the enchantress), Calypso (the goddess who keeps Odysseus captive), and Nausicaa (the princess who helps him). Each of these characters has a full entry in the Character Reference section of this guide.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">What Nolan Will Almost Certainly Draw On</div>
        <div class="book-author">The five elements at the heart of the poem</div>
        <div class="book-note">The Cyclops — Odysseus's most famous encounter, and a showcase for his cunning over brute strength. Circe — the enchantress who turns men into pigs and becomes Odysseus's lover. The Sirens — creatures whose song promises knowledge but means death. Calypso — the goddess who offers immortality in exchange for Odysseus giving up his homecoming. The suitors — the men who have taken over Odysseus's palace in his absence, courting his wife and eating his food. The poem's climax is Odysseus returning in disguise and destroying them all.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">The Nolan Connection — Non-Linear Storytelling</div>
        <div class="book-author">Why Homer and Nolan were made for each other</div>
        <div class="book-note">Nolan is famous for films that start in the middle and work backwards — Memento, Dunkirk, Tenet. The Odyssey is one of the earliest examples of this structure in all of literature. Homer begins ten years into the journey, with Odysseus trapped on Calypso's island. The famous wanderings — Cyclops, Sirens, Circe — are told in flashback by Odysseus himself at a dinner party. Homer invented the technique Nolan has made his signature. This is not a coincidence that Nolan chose this story.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="book-entry">
        <div class="book-title">A Reading Schedule</div>
        <div class="book-author">From now to July 17</div>
        <div class="book-note">You have roughly 15 weeks. At a comfortable pace of 2 books per week you will finish all 24 books with time to spare. Books 1-4 follow Telemachus (Tom Holland's character) — a slower start but essential setup. Books 5-12 are the famous wanderings — Circe, the Underworld, the Sirens, Scylla and Charybdis. Books 13-24 are the return to Ithaca and the reckoning with the suitors. If you only have time for one section before the film, read Books 9-12. That is the heart of what most people think of when they think of the Odyssey.</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
